MediatR is so commonly associated with Clean Architecture + CQRS in .NET that many teams adopt it by default. It is worth understanding both what it solves and where it adds noise.

**Pipeline behaviour example — validation:**
```csharp
public class ValidationBehaviour<TRequest, TResponse>
    : IPipelineBehavior<TRequest, TResponse>
    where TRequest : IRequest<TResponse>
{
    private readonly IEnumerable<IValidator<TRequest>> _validators;

    public async Task<TResponse> Handle(
        TRequest request, RequestHandlerDelegate<TResponse> next, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var failures = _validators
            .SelectMany(v => v.Validate(request).Errors)
            .Where(f => f is not null)
            .ToList();

        if (failures.Any())
            throw new ValidationException(failures);

        return await next();
    }
}
```
This runs before every handler without the handler knowing validation exists. The pipeline also naturally supports logging request/response times, wrapping handlers in a `TransactionScope`, or short-circuiting with a cached response.

**When to avoid MediatR:** simple services with 3-5 endpoints gain nothing. Direct constructor injection of a service is cleaner, more navigable, and easier to onboard new developers.

