**Decision matrix:**

| Data characteristic | Cache choice |
|---|---|
| Public, rarely changes (product images, JS bundles) | CDN (Azure CDN / Front Door) |
| Per-user data, multiple instances | Redis distributed cache |
| Computed aggregate, single instance OK | IMemoryCache |
| High read, low write, eventual consistency OK | Redis with long TTL |
| Must be always fresh | No cache — optimise the query instead |

**ASP.NET Core IMemoryCache example (Cache-Aside):**
```csharp
public async Task<ProductDto?> GetProductAsync(Guid id, CancellationToken ct)
{
    var cacheKey = $"product:{id}";
    if (!_cache.TryGetValue(cacheKey, out ProductDto? product))
    {
        product = await _db.Products.AsNoTracking()
            .Where(p => p.Id == id)
            .Select(p => new ProductDto(p.Id, p.Name, p.Price))
            .FirstOrDefaultAsync(ct);

        if (product is not null)
            _cache.Set(cacheKey, product, TimeSpan.FromMinutes(10));
    }
    return product;
}
```

**Cache invalidation on write:**
```csharp
public async Task UpdateProductAsync(UpdateProductCommand cmd, CancellationToken ct)
{
    // ... update in DB ...
    await _uow.CommitAsync(ct);
    _cache.Remove($"product:{cmd.Id}");  // explicit invalidation
}
```

**Redis IDistributedCache:** same pattern but survives instance restarts and is shared across pods — use for session, user-specific data, or any multi-instance scenario.

**What NOT to cache:** financial totals that must be real-time, personalised data without TTL safeguards, or anything that changes on every write.

**Escalation ladder (cheapest first):**

1. **CDN / Response caching** — zero cost at the API level; CDN serves the response.
2. **In-process IMemoryCache** — microsecond response for single-instance hot paths.
3. **Redis IDistributedCache** — millisecond response across all scaled instances.
4. **DB read replica** — offload SELECT traffic; Azure SQL Hyperscale supports up to 4 high-performance replicas.
5. **Horizontal API scaling** — add pods/instances; Azure Container Apps scales on HTTP request queue depth.
6. **CQRS read model** — pre-materialise complex queries in a separate store (Azure Cosmos DB, Elasticsearch) for sub-10ms reads at scale.

**EF Core read replica routing:**
```csharp
// In query handler — use read-optimised connection
services.AddDbContext<ReadDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseSqlServer(Configuration["ConnectionStrings:ReadReplica"]));

// Query handler
public class GetProductListHandler : IRequestHandler<GetProductListQuery, List<ProductDto>>
{
    private readonly ReadDbContext _db;
    // ...
    public Task<List<ProductDto>> Handle(GetProductListQuery q, CancellationToken ct)
        => _db.Products.AsNoTracking()
              .Where(p => p.CategoryId == q.CategoryId && p.IsActive)
              .OrderBy(p => p.Price)
              .Select(p => new ProductDto(p.Id, p.Name, p.Price))
              .ToListAsync(ct);
}
```

**Azure-specific options:**
- Azure SQL read scale-out (ApplicationIntent=ReadOnly in connection string).
- Azure Cache for Redis with geo-replication for global reads.
- Azure CDN / Front Door for edge caching.
- Azure Container Apps or AKS with KEDA for HTTP-driven autoscaling.
